Here is your **SHORT, POWERFUL & INTERVIEW-READY CHEAT SHEET** for

### ‚úÖ ViewBag vs ViewData vs TempData (ASP.NET MVC / ASP.NET Core)

ViewData => Dictionary (`ViewDataDictionary`)
ViewBag => Dynamic Object
TempData => Dictionary 

used to send data from controller to view 
> ViewBag and ViewData are used to pass data from controller to view for a single request, while TempData is used to persist data across requests mainly during redirects.(return RedirectToAction()) here TempData is used .
---

# üîπ Core Purpose

All three are used to **pass data from Controller to View**.

---

## ‚úÖ Comparison Table (Must-remember)

| Feature            | ViewData                          | ViewBag              | TempData                         |
| ------------------ | --------------------------------- | -------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| Type               | Dictionary (`ViewDataDictionary`) | Dynamic Object       | Dictionary                       |
| Type Safety        | ‚ùå No                              | ‚ùå No                 | ‚ùå No                             |
| Lifetime           | Current Request Only              | Current Request Only | Across Requests                  |
| Scope              | Controller ‚Üí View                 | Controller ‚Üí View    | Controller ‚Üí View ‚Üí Next Request |
| Persistence        | Not stored                        | Not stored           | Stored in Session                |
| Needs Type Casting | ‚úÖ Yes                             | ‚ùå No                 | ‚úÖ Yes                            |
| Redirect Support   | ‚ùå No                              | ‚ùå No                 | ‚úÖ Yes                            |

---

## ‚úÖ ViewData

```csharp
ViewData["Name"] = "Onkar";
```

In View:

```cshtml
@ViewData["Name"]
```

* Uses key-value pair
* Requires casting for complex objects
* Works only for same request

---

## ‚úÖ ViewBag

```csharp
ViewBag.Name = "Onkar";
```

In View:

```cshtml
@ViewBag.Name
```

* Wrapper over ViewData
* Uses dynamic
* Cleaner syntax

---

## ‚úÖ TempData

```csharp
TempData["Message"] = "Saved Successfully";
```

In View:

```cshtml
@TempData["Message"]
```

* Persists across redirect
* Uses Session internally
* Best for success/error messages

---

# üî• Real Usage Example

### Controller

```csharp
public IActionResult Demo()
{
    ViewData["A"] = "From ViewData";
    ViewBag.B = "From ViewBag";
    TempData["C"] = "From TempData";

    return RedirectToAction("Result");
}
```

### Result Action

```csharp
public IActionResult Result()
{
    return View();
}
```

### View (Result.cshtml)

```html
<p>@ViewData["A"]</p>   <!-- ‚ùå null -->
<p>@ViewBag.B</p>       <!-- ‚ùå null -->
<p>@TempData["C"]</p>   <!-- ‚úÖ works -->
```

---

# ‚úÖ Detailed Behaviour

| Scenario          | ViewData | ViewBag | TempData |
| ----------------- | -------- | ------- | -------- |
| Same View         | ‚úÖ        | ‚úÖ       | ‚úÖ        |
| RedirectToAction  | ‚ùå        | ‚ùå       | ‚úÖ        |
| Multiple Requests | ‚ùå        | ‚ùå       | ‚úÖ (once) |

---

# üß† Memory Trick

```
ViewData & ViewBag ‚Üí 1 request
TempData ‚Üí 2 requests
```

---

# ‚úÖ When to Use What?

| Situation                    | Best Choice           |
| ---------------------------- | --------------------- |
| Pass small data to same view | ViewBag               |
| Pass data after Redirect     | TempData              |
| Strong typing                | Model (Best Practice) |

---

# ‚ö° Interview One-liner

> ViewBag and ViewData are used to pass data from controller to view for a single request, while TempData is used to persist data across requests mainly during redirects.

---

# ‚úÖ Key Notes

* Prefer Model over all 3
* TempData is auto-cleared after read
* ViewBag internally uses ViewData

---







Sure üëç Let‚Äôs start **from absolute scratch** and build your understanding clearly.

---

# üß† First: Why do ViewBag, ViewData, TempData exist?

In ASP.NET MVC / ASP.NET Core:

* Controller processes data
* View displays data

So we need a way to **send data from Controller ‚Üí View**.
That‚Äôs where these three come in.

---

# ‚úÖ 1. ViewData ‚Äì The Base Concept

### What is ViewData?

ViewData is a dictionary used to pass data from controller to view.

### Syntax:

Controller:

```csharp
ViewData["Name"] = "Onkar";
```

View:

```cshtml
@ViewData["Name"]
```

### Characteristics:

* Key-value pair
* Exists only for CURRENT request
* Requires type casting for complex types

### Think of it as:

A bag of data that disappears once the page loads.

---

# ‚úÖ 2. ViewBag ‚Äì Friendly Version of ViewData

### What is ViewBag?

ViewBag is a dynamic wrapper over ViewData.

### Syntax:

Controller:

```csharp
ViewBag.Name = "Onkar";
```

View:

```cshtml
@ViewBag.Name
```

### Characteristics:

* No need for key string
* Same lifetime as ViewData
* Cleaner and readable
* Still not type-safe

### Internally:

```
ViewBag ‚Üí ViewData
```

So ViewBag is just syntactic sugar.

---

# ‚úÖ 3. TempData ‚Äì Data Across Requests

### What is TempData?

TempData is used when you want data available even AFTER redirect.

### Syntax:

Controller:

```csharp
TempData["msg"] = "Saved Successfully";
return RedirectToAction("Index");
```

View:

```cshtml
@TempData["msg"]
```

### Characteristics:

* Survives redirect
* Uses Session internally
* Data removed after one read

Used mainly for:
‚úî Success messages
‚úî Error alerts
‚úî Notifications

---

# üî• Core Differences at a Glance

| Feature          | ViewData        | ViewBag         | TempData     |
| ---------------- | --------------- | --------------- | ------------ |
| Type             | Dictionary      | Dynamic Object  | Dictionary   |
| Lifetime         | Current Request | Current Request | Next Request |
| Redirect Support | ‚ùå No            | ‚ùå No            | ‚úÖ Yes        |
| Storage          | Server Memory   | Server Memory   | Session      |
| Type Safety      | ‚ùå No            | ‚ùå No            | ‚ùå No         |

---

# ‚úÖ Practical Example

### Controller

```csharp
public IActionResult Save()
{
    ViewData["A"] = "Hello ViewData";
    ViewBag.B = "Hello ViewBag";
    TempData["C"] = "Hello TempData";

    return RedirectToAction("Result");
}
```

### Result View

```cshtml
<p>@ViewData["A"]</p>   <!-- null -->
<p>@ViewBag.B</p>       <!-- null -->
<p>@TempData["C"]</p>   <!-- Hello TempData -->
```

---

# üéØ Real-life analogy

* ViewData = Message written on whiteboard (erased after class)
* ViewBag = Sticky note (also removed after use)
* TempData = Message saved in diary for next day

---

# ‚úÖ When to Use

| Situation           | Recommended         |
| ------------------- | ------------------- |
| Same request data   | ViewBag or ViewData |
| Post-Redirect-Get   | TempData            |
| Strong data passing | Model (Best)        |

---

# ‚úÖ Interview-ready Summary

> ViewData and ViewBag are used to pass data from controller to view within the same request, but TempData preserves data across redirects using session, making it useful for one-time messages.

---

# ‚úÖ Quick Memory Trick

```
Same request ‚Üí ViewBag / ViewData  
Next request ‚Üí TempData
```

